0xffa833f0  0x00000008                                   . # e
0xffa833f0  0x0000000c                                   . # t
0xffa833f0  0x00000010                                   . # m
0xffa833f0  0x00000014                                   . # e
0xffa833f0  0x00000018                                   . # i
0xffa833f0  0x0000001c                                   . # n
Password Incorrect!
We can see that each letter increments var_ch by 4. Remember that sscanf in check takes a number (%d) as input. And because we didn’t provide any numbers, odds are that ‘4’ was probably some leftover data that happend to sit at the location of var_ch. This was never overwritten because sscanf didn’t encounter any numbers.
So let’s try giving it a number as input.
[0x08048508]&gt; wz "1234" @ 0xf3643010
[0x08048508]&gt; *esp+4=0xf3643010
[0x08048508]&gt; dr eip=sym.check
