Now we see what the function check is actually supposed to do: it increments the counter by each digit encountered. Or in other words it computes the digit sum, which has to land on 15 at some point during the computation.
And indeed, cleaning up the decompiled check makes this more obvious.
void sym.check(char *s)
{
    int32_t var_11h = 0;
    int32_t sum = 0;
    int32_t d;

    for(int i = 0; i &lt; strlen(s); i++) {
        var_11h = s[i];
        sscanf(&var_11h, "%d", &d);
        sum += d;
        if(sum == 0xf) {
            printf("Password OK!\n");
            exit(0);
        }
    }
    printf("Password Incorrect!\n");
    return;
}
